RIFT VALLEY FEVER - RWANDA: (WESTERN, SOUTHERN) CATTLE, HUMAN, OIE, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*******************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 12 Apr 2022
Source: OIE-WAHIS (World Animal Health Information System) 2022 [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=52182


Rift Valley fever virus (infection with), Rwanda
------------------------------------------------
General information
Report type: Immediate notification
Started: 28 Mar 2022
Confirmed: 28 Mar 2022
Reported: 9 Apr 2022
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence in a zone or a compartment
Causal agent: Rift Valley fever virus
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location 1: Kazo, Ngoma, Iburasirazuba [Western]
Started: 28 Mar 2022
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Cattle / 45 000 / 64 / 21 / 0 / 0 / 25 000
Affected population: Affected population are mostly cattle and possibly human.

Outbreak location 2: Gikonko, Gisagara, Amajyepfo [Southern]
Started: 4 Apr 2022
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Cattle / 32 000 / 9 / 3 / 0 / 0 / 17 250

Outbreak location 3: Kibilizi, Nyanza, Amajyepfo
Started: 4 Apr 2022
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Cattle / 35 000 / 13 / 5 / 0 / 0 / 14 500

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Vectors
Epidemiological comments: Massive vaccination and disinfection campaigns are ongoing.

Control measures at event level
Domestic control measures applied: Quarantine
Additional measures: Vaccination in response to the outbreak(s); surveillance within the restricted zone; surveillance outside the restricted zone; screening; official disposal of carcasses, by-products and waste; official destruction of animal products; movement control; disinfection; traceability

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Rubilizi National Veterinary Laboratory (national laboratory) / Cattle / Capture enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay for detection of immunoglobulin M (IgM-capture ELISA) / 28 Mar 2022 / Positive

[The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[According to the OIE WAHIS database, Rift Valley fever (animals) was last reported in Rwanda in June 2018. This event started in May 2018; the final follow-up report is available at https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=21996. According to this last report, the event was resolved. This event affected animals; no human cases were reported in Rwanda.

No human cases linked to this current outbreak have been reported, yet. However, in the description of the affected population (outbreak no. 1), it was mentioned that "the affected population is mostly cattle and possibly human. - Mod.CRD

